title: Grateful Dead Live at Nassau Veterans Memorial Coliseum on 1990-03-28
description:
Set 1:
d1t01 - Cold Rain And Snow ->
d1t02 - New Minglewood Blues
d1t03 - Easy To Love You
d1t04 - High Time
d1t05 - Queen Jane Approximately
d1t06 - Loose Lucy
d1t07 - Cassidy
d1t08 - Deal

Set 2:
d2t01 - Foolish Heart ->
d2t02 - Looks Like Rain ->
d2t03 - Cumberland Blues ->
d2t04 - The Weight
d2t05 - Hey Pocky Way ->
d2t06 - Drums ->
d3t01 - Space ->
d3t02 - The Other One
d3t03 - Wharf Rat ->
d3t04 - Good Lovin'

Encore:
d3t05 - Revolution

reviews.review_text:
Mr Miller is the best Great show and great sound.  Always listen to the Miller board -- he is the best!
4 stars show/setlist/sound
The 03/29 show is the best but 03/28 and 03/30 are also great.

Great Sleeper show from March of 1990 Honestly all of the better shows of the first half of 1990 were some of the best of the Dead's mature career. How can we deny the power of this show. It's obviously a baller night.

High Time & Loose Lucy in the same set makes me happy.

The second set though is where the magic really comes from. Yeah no extended Terrapin or Playin' jams, but just great renditions of great Dead songs/covers.

Foolish>LL Rain>Cumberland>Weight>Hey Pocky Way

Yeah, the only jammer is Foolish Heart, but every song is played with the utmost sincerity and effort. I can't think of better Dead versions of The Weight (and yes they did a good job with it), or LL Rain. 

The Cumberland absolutely SMOKES!! Jerry taking mad leads with intensity building and never at that high level again. 

Consider 1990 the last of the Dead revival stride. Sure some 91' shows are great, but really, this is the cream of the crop last of the greatest. This show is overshadowed by the excellent Branford appearance the next night, but don't oversee this show because you'll miss it. 

Other Excellent Grateful Dead 1990 Shows:
February 27th, March 14th-16th, March 19th, March 24th-26th, April 1st-3rd, June 6th-10, June 15-17, June 23rd-24th, July 12th, July 18th, September 18th-20th, December 12th

PEACE. It was never the same after 1990. I wasn't there, but the recordings do tell.

review good show overall. a really really good High Time. Brent sounds great. Pretty much every show The Dead played in March and April of 1990 was a gem. I recommend getting every show from 3/14/90 -> 4/3/90.  My favorite out of all of them has got to be 3/22/90.

We are all doing what we can... This was a great show! I had a blast.
The encore really put it over the top.

a REAL good time!! A college buddy scored multiple tickets for the entire Nassau run and offered me a seat for any night I chose.  Unavoidable scheduling conflicts made the first show the only realistic option for me. There was some incredible fungus amongus that night so for the longest time wasn’t sure if my memory of the evening was true.  The nine mile smile unfurled for the first time in ages upon hearing this. Between this recording (thanks to all those involved) and recently unearthed pictures it’s reassuring to know (25 years later) that both the show & incredible sunset that day were as awesome as I remember.   Thank you for a real good time indeed!

Start of 2nd New Yorker 3-dayer
Now that the following night has become the best-known of the tour, if not the year (specifically the 2nd set), this night seems overlooked (well, like the rest of the tour it does have an official release). It's not in the top handful of shows from the tour, but has certain standouts. This starts a 3-day run, which followed the 3-day run in Albany. The show is known for the first The Weight and the last Revolution. First Set. The entire set is above average; noticeably rolling into Minglewood (island phillies/on Long Island). I'm probably in the minority for loving Easy to Love You. It's Brent at his purest and most honest, I like the break, and Bobby and Jer liked playing this one. 3/15 was the best, but audio from this was used for Backstage Pass (the visual being later, from 7/6). High Time is a bit creaky and though Queen Jane is strong it's not, say 9/8. Loose Lucy is the 3rd one back and getting better. The rest is ten pounds of dynamite in a five pound bag. A slick Cassidy lifts the roof and a blow-out Deal leaves 'em happy for the half. Second Set. Foolish Heart is only the 2nd of '90, and one of the better ones; poignant and with an end jam that's not the end - Jer wants another run at the flubbed last verse... and still flubs (albeit not as much) for a 10min version. The 18th was the night for Looks Like Rain, though this is the familiar one from Without a Net (probably used because it has professional gloss and a brisk tempo). The Weight ain't bad - for the first one ever - but Hey Pocky is totally nailed. It's the 2nd of only 3 in '90 and arguably better than 7/22. The Other One is relatively brief @ just over 4min. All 3 Wharf Rats are big on this tour, but gimme this one. It has feedback notes from Jer, and a full stop with the band following Jer so tightly. The rest, like most of the set, is average '90. Revolution is the 2nd and last of the '90 return, but not as good as 3/15. 1st Set:  B 2nd Set: C Overall = 3¼ stars Highlights: Cassidy - dig this pat Cassidy Deal - blows huge Hey Pocky A-way - arguably best of late-Brent era Wharf Rat - biggest Wharf of tour (year?) SOURCES: The miller_87643 is the best SBD (though tunings are edited), but if you're not listening to the official, the exciting Tobin matrix is recommended instead. On the gorinsky_8510 SBD the volume is not as attenuated as the Miller or Tobin. The sbd-pc_miller is the pre-FM mix/feed. The provenance of the cutler_hollister_7510 is suspect. It claims it's lineage as SBD>24 Track>DAT, but why would you go from 2-track SBD OUTS to 24-trk? It would have to be 24-trk recorder>studio mixing board>2-trk>DAT. But if so, it would essentially be the released version on Spring 90 TOO. Given that it has the exact wave form of gorinsky_8510, you can surmise that the true lineage is SBD>DAT>PCM (reading between the lines, that makes more sense, too). Looks Like Rain is on Without a Net and Easy to Love You was used on the Backstage Pass video. The show is fuzzy on YouTube.

Hey Nassau Way! Great review from Mind_Wondrin. He marks the show at 3.25 stars. I'd give it another half a point on the strength of the second set, alone. The first set, though, while well-played, is missing something. Clocking in at around 53 minutes of music, it doesn't really pick up steam until the Loose Lucy. Then there's a strong Cassidy and a spirited Deal to close out the set that gets us primed for a great second set. The third quarter is where it's at. The nearly forty minutes from the foolish heart opener to pocky way marks this show's peak. Jerry even gets some dance moves in near its end; no question they're having fun with this run. Solid Wharf Rat in ballad slot.

In a word: different. Every show is different from every other show, of course, but the overall flow of this one is extra different, even for the Grateful Dead, and even for Spring ‘90. Don’t peek at the setlist. It’s so quirky that it's half the fun of the show. Just hit play. If you don’t mind spoilers or you’ve already dived in, read on.

Generally speaking, if you take a legendary Dead show and move one or two nights in either direction, you’ll find an equally good, but comparatively less famous show. 5/8/77 and 5/7/77. 10/1/94 and 10/3/94. 3/29/90 and 3/28/90. 

Different setlists, guest sit-ins, and/or levels of trading circulation result in successive shows varying from each other in popularity, even if they’re a relative match in terms of overall performance quality. I think all three of those factors play into this show receiving less fanfare than the show that occurred the following night. There’s no Dark Star, Bird Song, or Eyes. There’s no Branford. There’s no wealth of stoner uncles or shrewd high school English teachers recommending this to their deadhead students. In short, it doesn’t have nearly as much street cred as the Branford show, the Copps Coliseum gigs, or Phil’s birthday bash in Landover. This was night one of the Nassau run, a Wednesday warmup out on the island. The overshadowed sister of the famed show that would be played the following evening.

And yet, it’s so much more than that.  

3/28/90 keeps you guessing from the crack of the bat. The boys start off with a couple of pacy, edgy numbers dating back to their first album. Then, it’s three slow, floaty ballads from different eras and inspirations, each with marvelous vocal deliveries and mesmeric Garcia guitar solos, with Brent, Jerry, and Bob each building on the previous singer’s vision in kind. These really may be the best ever versions of Easy to Love You, High Time, and Queen Jane Approximately, respectively. Outstanding! Then it’s the newly revived Loose Lucy, a robust Cassidy, and an earnest Deal to close out the set. An ingenious first half of the show.

In the second set, each one of the five pre-Drums songs will have you thinking, “that’s an interesting spot in the setlist for (blank)”. Not to mention, each has an entirely different vibe than the last. Real setlist shenanigans, which I’m sure must’ve kept the attendees on their toes. As far as highlights, Bill Kreutzmann gets downright Appalachian on Cumberland Blues. As it comes to a boil, Phil takes the reins, Jerry lays it on thick, and the boys go ahead and get that puppy positively barking. As is often the case, space cadet Bob Weir masters Space, using MIDI effects that he’d eventually deploy on tunes like Here Comes Sunshine and Lucy in the Sky With Diamonds later in the ‘90s. Then, after all those curveballs and all that setlist trickery, post-Space they hit you right on the nose with a straightforward, smoldering The Other One > Wharf Rat > Good Lovin’ sequence. No gimmicks. No funny business. Just epic, herculean post-Space power. Jerry mutters through a shabbily-sung but well-played Beatles encore, and it’s a wrap.

This one is right in keeping with the overall excellence that is Spring 1990, but it’s also quite unique and different in its own right. An intricate musical maze, in which you eventually realize that the journey itself is actually the rewarding final destination. There’s no obvious peak to this show. It’s just a fun labyrinth. It keeps you grounded in the present, but keeps you guessing as to what they’ll have up their sleeve for you next just around the corner.
